The paper deals with approximation algorithms for clustering and low-rank approximation of binary matrices, which are problems that are commonly studied in computer science. The use of randomized linear time approximation schemes and the development of a novel sampling lemma suggest that the paper may belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) or cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-categories. Additionally, the use of approximation algorithms and the focus on clustering suggest that the paper may also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-categories. Finally, the use of linear algebra and the focus on low-rank approximation suggest that the paper may also belong to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category.
